Mots-cl=C3=A9s : Raisonnement, r=C3=A9vision, ontologie, logiques de descri=
ption,
m=C3=A9thode des tableaux


Abstract : This habilitation thesis outlines methods and tools resulting
from my research activities during the last nine years. These methods and
tools have been developed for reasoning and revision on knowledge bases
used in the context of the Semantic Web where data and knowledge stored in
these bases would be represented in a langage equipped with a formal and
unambiguous semantics. Such a formal semantics makes possible to develop an
automated mechanism for reasoning on the kind of such knowledge bases which
are called ontologies in this thesis. In order to address the requirements
for representing and exchanging data in the context of the Semantic Web,
description logics (a decidable fragment of First Order Logic) are used for
"encoding" the semantics of the language OWL (Ontology Web Language) that
was adopted by W3C. I was interested in developing algorithms and tools
which allow for processing data and knowledge represented in description
logics. My research therefore focuses on the three following topics. First,
it is the development of an optimized tableau method, called compressed
tableau, for reasoning on expressive ontologies. This method allows to
obtain a worst-case optimal algorithm in preserving the =C2=AB goal-oriente=
d =C2=BB
behavior of the standard tableau method, i.e. searching performed in a
reduced space. The method has been implemented in the prototype, named
Star=C3=A9, and evaluated with various ontologies. Second, I was interested=
 in
augmenting the expression power of description logics by adding the
transitive closure of binary relations which is known as an interesting
logical connector for knowledge modeling. By using the compressed tableau
method which allows not only for optimization but also for determining
decidability of a language, we have showed that a new language obtained by
fully combining an expressive description logic with the transitive closure
may be undecidable. This result led us to propose a restriction which
enables the new langage to be decidable. The third topic of my research is
concerned with expressive ontology revision. When adding new knowledge to
an ontology, it may become inconsistent. In order to restore consistency of
the ontology, it is needed to change the initial ontology in such a way
that the change should be minimal and the new knowledge should be taken
into account in the resulting ontology. We have proposed a revision method
which relies on a characterization of the semantics of an ontology by using
a finite set of graphs for representing ontology models. The method has
been implemented in the prototype available online, named OntoRev. Keywords
: Reasoning, revision, ontology, description logics, tableau method


Chan Le Duc

